  "market_context": "EUR/USD daily chart shows equal highs forming failure swings around 1.05, with a consolidation below. Price expands into a retracement and consolidates rather than continuing, setting up a draw on the unswept buy-side liquidity at the equal highs above.",
  "key_observation": "The equal highs are failure swings representing low resistance liquidity. After the consolidation low is swept and a bullish closure forms a daily swing low (low with higher low on each side), continuation into the equal highs is anticipated.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the daily chart, identify equal highs as failure swings and mark them as the draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Note the expansion into a retracement that fails to continue, classifying the structure as consolidation.",
    "Step 3: Wait for the consolidation low to be run out and look for a bullish closure to confirm a reversal.",
    "Step 4: Confirm a daily swing point — a low with a higher low on each side — anticipating next-day continuation toward the equal highs.",
    "Step 5: Mark the 0.5 (equilibrium) of the daily range and drop down to the 1-hour to refine entry, expecting the upper half to hold.",
    "Step 6: On the 1-hour, wait for SMT and a closure through the down-close candles; entry can be taken on that hourly closure with stop on the low targeting 2R.",
    "Step 7: Alternatively, drop to the 5-minute, wait for the closure through the series of candles forming the London-session low, and enter with stop below the bodies for 2R.",
    "Step 8: Manage trade as a London reversal / New York continuation toward the daily equal highs."
  ],
  "outcome": "2R target hit on both the 1-hour and 5-minute entry variations.",
  "lessons": "Failure swings (equal highs) act as low resistance liquidity and a high-probability draw. Daily bias from a swing-point closure dictates direction; lower time frames simply align. Multiple valid entries (1H closure or 5M confirmation) all achieve the 2R objective.",
